title: Syracuse councilor Jean Kessner 3 weeks late in filing NY campaign reports
text:
Syracuse councilor Jean Kessner 3 weeks late in filing NY campaign reports Jean_Kessner.JPG File photo: Syracuse Common Councilor Jean Kessner has not filed her campaign finance reports, which were due Sept. 21. (Teri Weaver | tweaver@syracuse.com) 
Kessner lost last month to Pam Hunter in a Democratic primary for the 128th Assembly District. 
Kessner raised nearly $9,000 in the challenge, according to her last filing, which was due before the primary. She spent a little more than $3,000, those older filings show. 
In the final days of that Democratic race, Kessner made a television ad. That spending does not show up on the reports already filed with the state. 
A call to Kessner this morning was not immediately returned. 
Hunter now faces Republican John Sharon in the Nov. 3 general election. Stott, a Democrat who also lost in the primary, remains on the ballot on the Conservative Party line. 
The 128th Assembly District includes parts of Syracuse and the towns of DeWitt, Onondaga and Salina. The seat was left open after Sam Roberts left to become the state's commissioner for welfare and disability programs.
